{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "In this essay I propose to look at the relationship between ethics and literature by looking at non-realistic forms of fiction, and at one work in particular, Joseph Heller's Catch-22.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "The topic is how non-realistic novels challenge our philosophical understanding of the relationship between literature and ethics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Non-realistic novels, then, depart from this general pattern in significant ways.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Joseph Heller's novel Catch-22 is a good example.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Heller's purpose in writing Catch-22 is decidedly moral.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "The novel is celebrated as one of the great antiwar novels, and Heller's writing was partly based by his own experience as a bombardier during World War II, and his own deeply held moral convictions.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "So in Catch-22 we have a novel with moral ideas at its center, but which employs non-realistic techniques of different kinds to reach and engage readers.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "If this message were all that the novel had to offer in terms of moral insight, it would not be terribly interesting.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "In what follows, I argue that the novel is much more imaginative and rich morally than this description indicates.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Further, the moral achievements of the book have everything to do with its non-realistic style.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "In this paper, I examine three questions regarding ethics and literature, and consider how these questions might be answered with regard to Catch-22.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "What emerges is a complex moral picture that does not fit what is usually said about the relationship between morality and works of literature.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "In Catch-22, however, imaginative resistance serves to engage the reader more fully with the events and ideas of the work.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The moral contradictions, like the logical ones, bring out the absurdity of the world in which the characters live.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Heller then uses this emotional distance itself to convey to the reader a sense of Yossarian's own detachment from his surroundings.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "This makes Yossarian's transformation at the end of the novel more powerful, as we, like him, are pulled into a less ironic, more deeply emotionally involved view of the events.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "In Catch-22, the perspective that provides excitement and emotional reward is not a characters' inner life but the author's ironic, distanced view of the world described in the novel.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "What is surprising about Heller's novel is just how emotionally engaging this somewhat detached perspective can be.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Imaginative resistance is properly thought of as a demerit in many realistic novels because of the way in which it interferes with the kind of engagement characteristic of realism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "In Catch-22, imaginative resistance is part of what makes the work engaging.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "The absurdities and moral outrages of the work provide much of the emotional substance that makes the book's quite acentral perspective emotionally rich.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "Catch-22, of course, prescribes a great deal of laughter.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "The absurdism of the scene allows us the moral freedom to laugh at what would otherwise be sacrosanct.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "We need a different means for judging when the responses called for by non-realistic novels are morally inappropriate.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "Real-life is a poor guide to the world of Catch-22.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "Non-realistic novels can have great moral significance (as successes or failures), but they achieve their aims by not using the standard techniques that characterize realistic fiction.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
